        "id": "de0e1243"
      },
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "## Q4 - Sigmoid Neuron: Implementation and Visualisation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "b6719c4c",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "b6719c4c"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "class SigmoidNeuron:\n",
        "\n",
        "    def __init__(self, weights, bias):\n",
        "        self.weights = np.array(weights, dtype=float)\n",
        "        self.bias = float(bias)\n",
        "\n",
        "    def forward(self, x):\n",
        "        z = np.dot(x, self.weights) + self.bias\n",
        "        return 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))\n",
        "\n",
        "    def numerical_gradient(self, x, h=1e-5):\n",
        "        grad_weights = np.zeros_like(self.weights)\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # Gradients for weights\n",
        "        for i in range(len(self.weights)):\n",
        "            orig = self.weights[i]\n",
        "            self.weights[i] = orig + h\n",
        "            f_plus = self.forward(x)\n",
        "            self.weights[i] = orig - h\n",
        "            f_minus = self.forward(x)\n",
        "            grad_weights[i] = (f_plus - f_minus) / (2 * h)\n",
        "            self.weights[i] = orig\n("
        "            \n",
        "        # Gradient for bias\n",
        "        orig_b = self.bias\n",
        "        self.bias = orig_b + h\n",
        "        f_plus_b = self.forward(x)\n",
        "        self.bias = orig_b - h\n",
        "        f_minus_b = self.forward(x)\n",
        "        grad_bias = (f_plus_b - f_minus_b) / (2 * h)\n",
        "        self.bias = orig_b\n",
        "        \n",
        "        return grad_weights, grad_bias"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "f2861779",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "f2861779"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Q4a - Forward Pass and Gradients\n",
        "\n",
        "For weights=[2, -1] and bias=0.5, compute the output and all gradients at x=[1, 1]. Explain what the gradient w.r.t. w1 means in plain English."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "78ee3a22",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "78ee3a22"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "neuron = SigmoidNeuron(weights=[2, -1], bias=0.5)\n",
        "x = np.array([1.0, 1.0])\n",
        "\n",
        "output = neuron.forward(x)\n",
        "grad_w, grad_b = neuron.numerical_gradient(x)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f'Output:        {output}')\n",
        "print(f'd(output)/dw1: {grad_w[0]:.6f}')\n",
        "print(f'd(output)/dw2: {grad_w[1]:.6f}')\n",
        "print(f'd(output)/db:  {grad_b:.6f}')"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "3c4a5b78",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3c4a5b78"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Explanation of gradient w.r.t. w1:**\n",
        "\n",
        "> **Your answer:**\n",
        "The gradient $\\frac{\\partial \\text{output}}{\\partial w_1}$ reflects the directional sensitivity of the neuron's activation with respect to $w_1$. In plain English, a value of $\\approx 0.149$ means that if we increase the weight $w_1$ by a tiny margin (e.g., $0.01$), the final probability output of this sigmoid neuron will increase by approximately $14.9\\%$ of that margin (e.g., $0.00149$)."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "0a7c2f21",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "0a7c2f21"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Q4b - Plot sigma(z) and sigma'(z)\n",
        "\n",
        "Plot sigma(z) and its derivative sigma'(z) = sigma(z)(1 - sigma(z)) for z in [-10, 10].\n",
        "\n",
        "- At what value of z is the gradient largest?\n",
        "- What happens as z approaches +/- infinity and why is this a problem (vanishing gradient)?\n",
        "\n",
        "> **Your answer:**\n",
        "* The gradient reaches its maximum value of $0.25$ exactly at $z = 0$.\n",
        "* As $z \\to \\pm\\infty$, the derivative $\\sigma'(z)$ flattens to zero. This is known as the **vanishing gradient problem**—when the values of $z$ are large and saturated, updates via backpropagation stall because multiplying downstream gradients by almost zero effectively halts the network's optimization process."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "ae24f853",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ae24f853"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "z = np.linspace(-10, 10, 500)\n",
        "\n",
        "sigma       = 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))\n",
        "sigma_prime = sigma * (1.0 - sigma)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(z, sigma, label=r'$\\sigma(z)$', color='blue')\n",
        "plt.plot(z, sigma_prime, label=r\"$\\sigma'(z)$\", color='orange', linestyle='--')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('z')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Value')\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "plt.title('Sigmoid and its derivative')\n",
        "plt.grid(True)\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
    {
