        "id": "f6c6a3c4"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Q4c - Is sigma(100z) basically a perceptron?\n",
        "\n",
        "A classmate claims: 'a sigmoid neuron with weights multiplied by 100 is basically the same as a perceptron.'\n",
        "\n",
        "Plot sigma(100z) vs sigma(z) vs the step function. Is the claim correct? Under what condition does it break down?\n",
        "\n",
        "> **Your answer:**\n",
        "Yes, the claim is accurate for almost all practical operational input profiles because scaling the values by 100 heavily steepens the transition zone into an abrupt threshold boundary. However, the claim **breaks down exactly at $z = 0$**. At $z = 0$, the continuous sigmoid function evaluates precisely to $0.5$, whereas a standard step perceptron switches cleanly to either $0$ or $1$ depending on how its inequality operator is defined."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "25e14933",
