        "---\n",
        "## Q5 - Gradient Descent on a Toy Regression Problem\n",
        "\n",
        "A single-layer network (one input, one output, no activation) must learn y = 3x + 1."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "2cd41a39",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2cd41a39"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "X_train = np.array([0.0, 1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0])\n",
        "y_train = np.array([1.0, 4.0, 7.0, 10.0, 13.0])"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "aada2ca5",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "aada2ca5"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Q5a - Analytical Gradients + Full-Batch GD\n",
        "\n",
        "Derive dC/dw and dC/db analytically (show algebra). Implement full-batch GD with eta = 0.01 for 200 epochs. Plot the loss curve. Do w and b converge to 3 and 1?\n",
        "\n",
        "**Derivation (show algebra):**\n",
        "\n",
        "> **Your answer:**\n",
        "Prediction: $a_x = w \\cdot x + b$. Cost function: $C = \\frac{1}{2n} \\sum_x (a_x - y_x)^2$.\n",
        "Using the chain rule:\n",
        "$$\\frac{\\partial C}{\\partial w} = \\frac{1}{2n} \\sum_x 2(w \\cdot x + b - y_x) \\cdot \\frac{\\partial (w \\cdot x + b)}{\\partial w} = \\frac{1}{n} \\sum_x (w \\cdot x + b - y_x) \\cdot x$$\n",
        "$$\\frac{\\partial C}{\\partial b} = \\frac{1}{2n} \\sum_x 2(w \\cdot x + b - y_x) \\cdot \\frac{\\partial (w \\cdot x + b)}{\\partial b} = \\frac{1}{n} \\sum_x (w \\cdot x + b - y_x)$$"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "27111514",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "27111514"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "w, b = 0.0, 0.0\n",
        "eta = 0.01\n",
        "losses = []\n",
        "n = float(len(X_train))\n",
        "\n",
        "for epoch in range(200):\n",
        "    predictions = w * X_train + b\n",
        "    errors = predictions - y_train\n",
        "    loss = (1.0 / (2 * n)) * np.sum(errors ** 2)\n",
        "    losses.append(loss)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    dw = (1.0 / n) * np.sum(errors * X_train)\n",
        "    db = (1.0 / n) * np.sum(errors)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    w = w - eta * dw\n",
        "    b = b - eta * db\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f'Final w = {w:.4f}, b = {b:.4f}')\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(7, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(losses)\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Epoch')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Loss')\n",
        "plt.title('Full-Batch GD (eta=0.01)')\n",
        "plt.grid(True)\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "c4f47adf",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "c4f47adf"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Q5b - SGD with Mini-Batch Size = 1\n",
        "\n",
        "Implement SGD with batch size 1. Train 200 epochs with eta = 0.01. Plot the loss curve. How does it differ from full-batch? Explain in terms of gradient quality and noise.\n",
        "\n",
        "> **Your answer:**\n",
        "The SGD loss curve is significantly noisier and exhibits sharp oscillations compared to the smooth, monotonic decline seen in full-batch gradient descent. This happens because full-batch GD computes the exact gradient across the entire dataset, whereas SGD estimates the gradient using a single random example. This single-sample estimate introduces significant variance (noise), but the stochastic paths help avoid local minima in complex optimization landscapes."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "477ace3b",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "477ace3b"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "np.random.seed(42)  # For reproducible sampling path\n",
        "w, b = 0.0, 0.0\n",
        "eta = 0.01\n",
        "losses_sgd = []\n",
        "num_samples = len(X_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "for epoch in range(200):\n",
        "    # Track total epoch loss for plotting purposes\n",
        "    epoch_preds = w * X_train + b\n",
        "    epoch_loss = (1.0 / (2 * num_samples)) * np.sum((epoch_preds - y_train) ** 2)\n",
        "    losses_sgd.append(epoch_loss)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # SGD Step: loop over shuffled indices\n",
        "    indices = np.random.permutation(num_samples)\n",
        "    for idx in indices:\n",
        "        xi = X_train[idx]\n",
        "        yi = y_train[idx]\n",
        "        pred = w * xi + b\n",
        "        err = pred - yi\n",
        "        \n",
        "        # For n=1\n",
        "        dw = err * xi\n",
        "        db = err\n",
        "        \n",
        "        w = w - eta * dw\n",
        "        b = b - eta * db\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f'Final w = {w:.4f}, b = {b:.4f}')\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(7, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(losses_sgd, color='orange')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Epoch')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Loss')\n",
        "plt.title('SGD batch=1 (eta=0.01)')\n",
        "plt.grid(True)\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "id": "1935cf53",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "1935cf53"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Q5c - Divergence with eta = 0.5\n",
        "\n",
        "Set eta = 0.5 with full-batch GD. Show the loss curve and explain using the gradient formulas from Q5a why it diverges.\n",
        "\n",
        "> **Your answer:**\n",
        "With an excessively high learning rate like $\\eta = 0.5$, the steps skip clean over the valley of the objective function. Mathematically, the gradient components scale proportional to $X^2$. Because elements in $X_{\\text{train}}$ go up to $4.0$, $\\frac{1}{n}\\sum X^2$ is large, meaning the gradient step size heavily outpaces the distance to the minimum. Each parameter correction overcorrects so aggressively that the loss diverges exponentially toward infinity."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": null,
      "id": "4218aa31",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "4218aa31"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "w, b = 0.0, 0.0\n",
        "eta_high = 0.5\n",
        "losses_div = []\n",
        "n = float(len(X_train))\n",
        "\n",
        "for epoch in range(50):\n",
        "    predictions = w * X_train + b\n",
        "    errors = predictions - y_train\n",
        "    loss = (1.0 / (2 * n)) * np.sum(errors ** 2)\n",
        "    losses_div.append(loss)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    if not np.isfinite(loss):\n",
        "        print(f'Diverged at epoch {epoch}')\n",
        "        break\n",
        "        \n",
        "    dw = (1.0 / n) * np.sum(errors * X_train)\n",
        "    db = (1.0 / n) * np.sum(errors)\n",
        "    \n",
        "    w = w - eta_high * dw\n",
        "    b = b - eta_high * db\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(7, 4))\n",
        "plt.plot(losses_div, color='red')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Epoch')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Loss')\n",
        "plt.title('Full-Batch GD (eta=0.5) - Divergence')\n",
        "plt.grid(True)\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
